---
import DocsLayout from "../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
---

<DocsLayout title="Core Concepts">
  <h1>Core Concepts</h1>
  <p class="docs-subtitle">
    The six building blocks of every soundtrack pack.
  </p>

  <h2>Soundtrack Pack</h2>
  <p>
    A <strong>SoundtrackPack</strong> is the top-level container. It holds
    metadata and five ordered arrays: assets, stems, scenes, bindings, and
    transitions. Every pack has a unique <code>id</code>,
    <code>version</code>, and <code>schemaVersion</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Assets</h2>
  <p>
    An <strong>AudioAsset</strong> represents a single audio file reference.
    Assets have a <code>kind</code> that determines playback behavior:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Kind</th><th>Behavior</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>loop</code></td><td>Plays continuously, typically the backbone of a scene.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>oneshot</code></td><td>Plays once — fanfares, impacts, stabs.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>stinger</code></td><td>Short punctuation clip, often used during scene transitions.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>ambient</code></td><td>Environmental texture — wind, rain, crowd murmur.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Optional fields: <code>bpm</code>, <code>key</code>,
    <code>loopStartMs</code>/<code>loopEndMs</code> for loop trimming, and
    <code>tags</code> for organization.
  </p>

  <h2>Stems</h2>
  <p>
    A <strong>Stem</strong> wraps an asset with playback instructions. It links
    to an asset by <code>assetId</code> and adds:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>role</code> — semantic purpose: <code>base</code>, <code>danger</code>, <code>combat</code>, <code>boss</code>, <code>recovery</code>, <code>mystery</code>, <code>faction</code>, <code>accent</code></li>
    <li><code>loop</code> — whether to loop or play once</li>
    <li><code>gainDb</code> — volume offset in decibels</li>
    <li><code>mutedByDefault</code> — starts muted, can be unmuted dynamically</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Scenes</h2>
  <p>
    A <strong>Scene</strong> defines what plays during a particular game state.
    Each scene has a <code>category</code> (exploration, tension, combat, boss,
    victory, aftermath, stealth, safe-zone) and a list of <strong>layers</strong>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Each layer references a stem, and optionally marks it as <code>required</code>
    (must play) or specifies a <code>startMode</code> (immediate, next-bar,
    after-transition).
  </p>
  <p>
    The <code>fallbackSceneId</code> lets you define graceful degradation: if a
    scene cannot play (e.g. missing assets), the engine falls back.
  </p>

  <h2>Bindings</h2>
  <p>
    A <strong>TriggerBinding</strong> maps game-state conditions to scenes.
    Each binding has:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>conditions</code> — an array of field/op/value rules (all must match)</li>
    <li><code>priority</code> — higher priority bindings win when multiple match</li>
    <li><code>stopProcessing</code> — if true, no lower-priority bindings are evaluated after this one matches</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Condition operators: <code>eq</code>, <code>neq</code>, <code>gt</code>,
    <code>gte</code>, <code>lt</code>, <code>lte</code>, <code>includes</code>.
    Fields are arbitrary strings — your game defines what they mean.
  </p>

  <h2>Transitions</h2>
  <p>
    A <strong>TransitionRule</strong> defines how one scene flows into another.
    Transitions are keyed by <code>fromSceneId</code> →
    <code>toSceneId</code> and specify a <code>mode</code>:
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Mode</th><th>Behavior</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>immediate</code></td><td>Hard cut — old scene stops, new scene starts instantly.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>crossfade</code></td><td>Both scenes overlap for <code>durationMs</code>.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>bar-sync</code></td><td>Waits until the next musical bar boundary, then switches.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>stinger-then-switch</code></td><td>Plays a stinger asset, then switches to the new scene.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>cooldown-fade</code></td><td>Gradual fade-out of old scene before starting the new one.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Runtime Pack</h2>
  <p>
    The <strong>RuntimeSoundtrackPack</strong> is the exported, game-ready
    version of a pack. It strips editor-only fields (names on bindings,
    notes on scenes/transitions) and preserves only what a game engine needs.
    Use the Export screen in the studio to produce this format.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
